### CA results


RT of participants

Individual trials:

  1. All trials that have a response time less than 1 second or more than 30 seconds

  2. From the remaining trails we will exclude all trials with a response time greater than median + 3 SD or less than median – 3 SD, where the median is calculated individually for each participant and each condition (simple versus simple; complex versus complex; simple versus complex)

  3. Participants for whom we remove more than 50% of trials will be completely removed

One sample t test comparing the mean choice proportion of stochastic dominant option against the 50% benchmark for trials in each condition separately.

Expected results: The choice proportion of stochastic dominant option will be significantly greater than 50%.

One sample t test comparing the mean choice proportion of complex options against the 50% benchmark for trials in simple versus complex conditions.

Hypothesis 1.3

• Two-sample t test comparing participant-level median response times in simple versus simple condition against complex versus complex condition. We expect slower response times in simple versus simple condition than in complex versus complex condition.

Results:


Condition median_cc median_ss t_value df p_value conf_interval_lower conf_interval_upper

• Two-sample t test comparing Coefficient of EV in a logistic regression on choice in simple versus simple condition against complex versus complex condition in a mixed-effects regression participant-level intercept and slope.

We expect higher Coefficient of EV in simple versus simple condition than in complex versus complex condition.

• Two-sample t test comparing percentage of risky choices in simple versus simple condition against complex versus complex condition. We have no theoretical reasons to expect a significant difference when we assume that complexity might increase processing noise equally for risky and not the risky (in terms of variance) options.

separate t-tests for just the subset of trials were the complex option is right-skwed as well as for the subset of trials were the complex option is left-skewed.
